WEBVTT

00:00:00.036 --> 00:00:01.384
<i>Previously on The Last Ship</i>

00:00:01.581 --> 00:00:03.070
- Do you miss it, sir?
- Miss what?

00:00:03.200 --> 00:00:04.067
War.

00:00:04.094 --> 00:00:07.295
Gustavo Barros has inspired
all of South America

00:00:07.301 --> 00:00:08.301
He's a revolutionary.

00:00:08.374 --> 00:00:11.864
<i>Americans, We will no longer
cower in fear of your big stick.</i>

00:00:12.026 --> 00:00:13.927
This is a full-scale invasion.

00:00:13.983 --> 00:00:16.287
Emergency shut-down.
Shut everything down!

00:00:16.335 --> 00:00:17.801
Take cover!

00:00:18.030 --> 00:00:20.395
<i>If the United States wants a fight,
you will lose.</i>

00:00:20.403 --> 00:00:22.299
The US Navy fleet in Florida
was just attacked.

00:00:22.301 --> 00:00:23.437
All the ships were sunk,

00:00:23.461 --> 00:00:25.560
but for what comes next,
we're on the front line.

00:00:25.563 --> 00:00:27.226
If I'm gonna die,
I'm going down with the ship.

00:00:27.250 --> 00:00:28.444
We're at war.

00:00:29.650 --> 00:00:31.945
<i>Earlier today,
the United States of America</i>

00:00:31.955 --> 00:00:33.475
<i>was suddenly
and without provocation...</i>

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:34.879
Alisha, are you there?

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:35.880
Yeah, honey, I'm here.

00:00:36.444 --> 00:00:37.100
I was so worried.

00:00:37.101 --> 00:00:39.029
You know, the...
The... the attack.

00:00:39.030 --> 00:00:41.370
Y-You didn't say
you were going to Mayport,

00:00:41.371 --> 00:00:42.719
and your friends were there.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:44.190
So I thought maybe you went, and...

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.789
Baby, I'm just so happy
to hear your voice.

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:50.589
I'm okay.
Are you all right?

00:00:50.590 --> 00:00:52.859
No.
I mean... yeah, yeah.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.060
I-I'm fine.
I'm just freaking out a little.

00:00:55.070 --> 00:00:56.869
Those ships...
Are they all gone?

00:00:56.870 --> 00:00:58.730
Is there gonna be another attack?

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:00.539
They're not saying
anything new on TV.

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:02.400
Honey, don't watch the TV.

00:01:02.410 --> 00:01:03.939
Everything's going to be okay.

00:01:03.940 --> 00:01:05.070
I promise.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:07.139
Look, I... I got to be here
a little while longer,

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:08.879
but I'll call you
as soon as I can, okay?

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:11.279
We got a lot of good people
working hard to keep us safe.

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:13.619
Everything's gonna be okay.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:16.080
Y-You need to call me soon.

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:19.089
Let me know what's going on. Let
me know you're okay. Promise?

00:01:19.090 --> 00:01:21.089
<i>I have therefore
asked the Congress</i>

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:23.029
<i>to declare a State of War</i>

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:28.159
<i>between the United States
and the Gran Colombian Empire.</i>

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:29.229
I promise.

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:30.499
I love you.

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:32.299
Yeah, I love you, too.

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:33.569
<i>Absolute victory.</i>

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:35.700
<i>May God bless
the United States of America.</i>

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:39.109
<i>The President has declared war</i>

00:01:39.110 --> 00:01:41.509
<i>against
the Gran Colombian Empire.</i>

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:44.249
Tom.
It's good to see you.

00:01:44.250 --> 00:01:46.919
You, too, Joe. No
word from the <i>James.</i>

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:49.580
They won't call until it's safe.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:52.119
Anything from our team in Panama?

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:54.459
Nothing yet.
But no news is good news.

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:57.059
General. Russ.

00:01:57.060 --> 00:01:59.260
- Admiral.
- My Marines?

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:03.730
They're starting a body count.

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.739
Doesn't do it justice.

00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:10.139
They hit us hard.

00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:13.209
Admiral, the reports
are still dribbling in,

00:02:13.210 --> 00:02:16.279
but Panama has definitely
thrown in with Gustavo.

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:18.149
Costa Rica and Ecuador
are on the brink.

00:02:18.150 --> 00:02:20.079
If a domino effect
starts in the region,

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:21.619
we could be in real trouble.

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:23.889
Gustavo won't stop
south of our border.

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:25.950
How are we supposed to defend
against a second attack

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:27.959
if we don't even know
how the first one happened

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:29.820
or if we can even
recover from it?

00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:31.930
I know someone
who can help with that.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.629
A student of mine
at the Academy.

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:36.899
A midshipman?

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:38.499
Clayton Swain.

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:39.969
He saw this attack coming.

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:42.369
Master Chief, we need to find him
and bring him here.

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:43.839
Yes, sir.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:45.709
We need to deploy
all our available assets.

00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:47.709
If it floats, flies,
or rolls, it fights.

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:49.579
Agreed.
We need every piece of intel

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:52.110
we have on Central
and South America...

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:53.579
Air and Naval assets,
troop levels,

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.980
- centers of gravity... everything.
- Wait.

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:58.650
Are you talking about
sending our assets south?

00:02:58.660 --> 00:03:00.859
We have no command and control.

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:03.059
I can't get a single
field commander on the phone.

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:04.659
How are we supposed to come up

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:06.129
with a global strategic plan?

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:07.329
He's right.

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:08.999
The President may have declared war,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.599
but right now we don't have
a military to fight it.

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:12.869
We've got nothing.

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:14.600
Not true.

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:16.740
We have <i>Nathan James.</i>

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:26.879
Many of you here
are new to the Navy...

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:28.880
new to this ship.

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:32.019
Some of you,
we've been here before.

00:03:32.020 --> 00:03:36.220
Either way,
what happened in Mayport

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:39.829
is not something
you ever get used to.

00:03:39.830 --> 00:03:41.499
It hurts.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:43.429
And it was meant to hurt.

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:46.899
That's what our enemy wanted to do.

00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:49.570
And today, he succeeded.

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:54.239
It caught us off guard,

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:59.310
sent a powerful message,
trying to shake our resolve.

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:03.720
But a war isn't lost
because we're hurt.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.120
For over 200 years,
the United States Navy has

00:04:09.130 --> 00:04:13.729
built, sustained, and protected
its war-fighting culture.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:15.529
This attack doesn't change that.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.869
In fact, it will once again
bring out the best in us.

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:22.139
Our enemies
have underestimated us.

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:26.139
And if you doubt that,
look back at the past few years.

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.480
Look at the people
who've been on this ship.

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:32.149
When trouble arises,

00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:35.019
we have proven
time and time again,

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:37.749
no matter the enemy,
no matter the odds,

00:04:37.750 --> 00:04:40.959
one ship can do it.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:44.690
<i>This</i> ship can do it.

